AU  - M. Zhu
AU  - X. Zheng
AU  - J. Cao
AU  - Y. Liu
AU  - L. Huang
T2  - 2025 8th International Conference on Transportation Information and Safety (ICTIS)
AB  - To enhance the efficiency of ship scheduling in port waters, this study leverages Cyber-Physical System (Cyber physical system, CPS) technology to address the limitations of traditional port systems, which have been hindered by insufficient interconnection and interoperability. CPS technology, based on the interaction and feedback loops between information and physical systems, allows for precise monitoring and effective control of physical environments. In this study, CPS technology is integrated into the port berth scheduling optimization problem, aiming to develop a robust optimization model and methodology. Firstly, a finite state machine dynamic model is established for the port’s waiting area, channel area and berth area, considering essential factors such as ship compatibility, berth size, and water depth safety. Then, using mixed logic dynamic modeling principles, a dynamic operational model is built for ships navigating the channel area, factoring in changing visibility and environmental influences such as wind and waves. To further enhance the computational efficiency during optimization, an event-triggered adaptive horizon model predictive control (Event-Triggered Adaptive Horizon Model Predictive Control, ETAHMPC) method is developed. A case study simulation at Wuhan Port demonstrates that the proposed model and method outperform traditional model predictive control algorithms, achieving superior berth allocation with reduced computational overhead. This research contributes to the advancement of port berth scheduling systems by better adapting to the evolving demands of information-driven port operations.
C3  - 2025 8th International Conference on Transportation Information and Safety (ICTIS)
