TI  - AGV Vehicle Dynamics Optimization in Automated Logistics Warehousing Systems
AU  - F. Hong
AU  - J. Ye
AU  - Z. Liu
AU  - J. Deng
AU  - Y. Xu
AU  - Y. Zheng
T2  - 2025 11th International Symposium on Sensors, Mechatronics and Automation System (ISSMAS)
AB  - An analysis was conducted on the dynamic characteristics and optimization problems of AGV vehicles in the Automated Logistics Warehouse System (ALWS). As the core execution unit of modern warehousing and logistics, AGV system achieves efficient and stable material handling operations through the collaborative optimization of multi-body dynamics modeling, drive control algorithms, and path planning technology. In terms of technical implementation, the AGV dynamic optimization system can be divided into the following core modules: the environment perception module based on inertial measurement unit (IMU) and laser SLAM achieves centimeter level positioning accuracy; The motion control module considering incomplete constraints integrates adaptive PID and model predictive control (MPC) algorithms; Adopt torque optimization strategy for power distribution modules under different load conditions; The virtual debugging module supported by digital twin technology has achieved online calibration of dynamic parameters. By establishing a multi rigid body dynamic model of AGV, this study quantitatively analyzed the influence mechanism of geometric parameters of steering mechanism and tire lateral stiffness on path tracking accuracy. An improved hybrid evaluation model was proposed in the study, which combines entropy weight method to determine the weights of dynamic indicators and introduces time series analysis to quantify the stability of AGV motion. Test data shows that the optimized AGV system reduces trajectory deviation error to within ± 10mm at a running speed of 1.5m/s, and the impact of emergency stop conditions decreases by 37%. Although dynamic optimization has increased the average operational efficiency of AGVs by 28%, there is still a 12% control delay phenomenon in high dynamic storage environments. The nonlinear characteristics of transmission systems and the coupling effect of distributed drives are currently the main technical bottlenecks. Our future research should focus on breaking through adaptive control strategies based on deep reinforcement learning. This study verifies the key role of dynamic optimization in extending the service life of AGVs - by reducing mechanical vibration losses, the service life of key components can be increased by about 30%, providing a new technological path for AGV lifecycle cost control.
