TY  - CONF
TI  - The Optimal Resource Allocation Across Multiple Links in Cyber Twin Based Edge Cloud
AU  - A. Wu
AU  - G. Wu
T2  - ICC 2023 - IEEE International Conference on Communications
AB  - The existing network infrastructure has been suffering from the unification of network addresses and user identification for decades. However, the rise of the metaverse presents a way to use cyber twins as user identification while mapping it to network addresses dynamically, hence realizing the locator-identity separation in networks. Since this approach brings changes to network architecture, a new network architecture is proposed in this paper. The cyber twin acts as a communication broker which manages the communication resources across multiple communication modes for its corresponding physical entity, thus allowing the convergence of multiple communication modes. The cyber twin is assumed to obtain communication resources such as bandwidth from multiple communication systems including WiFi, 4G/5G, Lora, etc. The physical entity corresponding to the cyber twin has multiple terminal devices that support all the communication modes. The resource allocation problem in the proposed scenario can be formulated as an optimization problem. A parallel Deep Reinforcement Learning (DRL) algorithm is proposed to solve this problem. The algorithm utilizes multiple deep neural networks in parallel to reduce overestimation and increase the stability of network training. Simulation results show that the proposed algorithm achieves significant performance improvement compared with the state-of-the-art solutions.
