TY  - CONF
TI  - Simulation-Based Optimization and Analysis of an Automotive Hot Stamping Production Line: a Case Study
AU  - X. Cai
AU  - X. Zhang
AU  - Y. Liu
T2  - 2025 9th International Conference on Electrical, Mechanical and Computer Engineering (ICEMCE)
AB  - Lightweight automotive design has accelerated the adoption of hot stamping technology, yet many small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) still operate production lines with low efficiency, unbalanced cycle times, and rigid logistics. To address these challenges, this study develops a simulation-based optimization framework for a hot stamping production line at Ningbo Heli Mould Co., Zhejiang, China. A baseline Plant Simulation model was constructed and calibrated using real operational data of 1.2 mm and 1.5 mm ultra-high-strength steel sheets. Bottleneck analysis based on the Theory of Constraints (TOC) identified key limitations, including mismatched furnacepress cycle times, insufficient buffering, and inflexible AGV routing. To overcome these constraints, an integrated optimization strategy was proposed, combining physical layout improvements (AGV reconfiguration and robotic buffering) with sequencing optimization via a genetic algorithm (GA). Comparative simulation experiments showed that layout optimization contributed the most significant cycle time reduction, while sequencing optimization provided marginal yet complementary improvements. Partial industrial validation further confirmed that simulation-derived gains translated into measurable efficiency improvements in practice. The study demonstrates the potential of combining discrete-event simulation with targeted optimization strategies to enhance SME hot stamping lines, providing both academic insights and actionable industrial implications.
