AU  - Z. Huang
AU  - H. Ma
AU  - H. Wen
AU  - L. Ma
AU  - Z. Zhang
AU  - X. Wang
AU  - Z. Xia
T2  - 2024 30th International Conference on Mechatronics and Machine Vision in Practice (M2VIP)
AB  - With the advent of the Ship 4.0 era, human factors engineering has become crucial in ship operation system design to handle complex sea conditions and high- intensity tasks, thereby enhancing operational efficiency and safety.This study aims to investigate the impact of interface optimization on the operational accuracy of ship operators under varying sea conditions, as monitored by the Human-Cyber-Physical Systems (HCPS). The experiment was conducted at the Jiangsu Maritime National Simulation Training Center, simulating sea wave conditions at levels 4, 5, and 6. A total of 48 maritime cadets, aged 21±2, participated in manually navigating ships around reefs. Through the HCPS system, real-time monitoring and analysis of the cadets' heart rate, electromyography (EMG), and inertial navigation data were performed. Simulator Sickness Questionnaire (SSQ) and Motion Sickness Susceptibility Questionnaire (MSQ) were utilized to quantify the cadets' motion sickness indices, assessing the impact of interface design on the operational tasks under motion conditions. The results showed that the optimized interface significantly improved the cadets' operational accuracy under complex sea conditions while effectively alleviating motion sickness symptoms. This study provides empirical support for future ship operation interface design, highlighting the necessity and importance of optimizing interfaces for motion conditions.
