TI  - Optimization of Computational Complexity of Digital Model of Stacker Crane Electric Drive
AU  - A. Nakataev
AU  - A. Ziuzev
AU  - M. Mudrov
T2  - 2025 International Ural Conference on Electrical Power Engineering (UralCon)
AB  - This paper examines the computational complexity of implementing digital models for automated warehouse complexes with a group of stacker cranes. When optimizing peak power consumption for groups of electric drives, detailed models of fifth-order asynchronous motors create significant computational barriers to simulating dozens of drives in real time. The study proposes using simplified first-order models based on separating the time scales of electromagnetic (milliseconds) and mechanical (seconds) transients. A comparative analysis was conducted using three models in Matlab/Simulink: a fifth-order motor model with vector control and two first-order models (with and without a current loop). Simulation results for 10 stacker cranes (30 electric drives) show that the fifth-order model exhibits a nonlinear increase in computational time, while the first-order models maintain a linear increase in simulation time. A simplified model without a current control loop provides a 56% simulation speedup compared to the model with a current loop (0.44 s versus 0.78 s for a 10 -second simulation), while maintaining acceptable peak power estimation accuracy. A key finding is the ability to use mechanical power instead of active power for energy optimization tasks, as losses follow similar patterns with proportionality coefficients. The typical 8% overshoot of the current loop does not significantly affect the accuracy of peak power estimation, as the maximum power occurs in the position control phases without current overshoot. The proposed approach enables real-time optimization of electric drive groups for industrial digital models, providing a practical balance between computational efficiency and simulation accuracy for predictive energy management systems.
