TI  - A Standards-Simulation-Evaluation Framework (SSEF) for System-Level Modeling and Parameter Optimization of Hydraulic Tensioning Systems
AU  - Y. Cao
T2  - IEEE Access
AB  - Simulation models for standard-governed engineering systems often treat regulatory compliance as an afterthought, leaving parameter–performance relationships opaque and providing no clear path from simulation outputs to practical design decisions. This paper presents a Standards-Simulation-Evaluation Framework (SSEF) for modeling and parameter optimization of quay crane trolley hydraulic tensioning systems. The framework embeds EN 13001 load definitions directly into the simulation as boundary constraints, so the standard drives the analysis rather than sitting outside it as a checklist. Using an AMESim model, 28 hydraulic parameter configurations were simulated and evaluated through a two-layer scheme combining six dynamic performance indicators with a wire rope fatigue damage index. A distance-to-ideal-point ranking method inspired by the Technique for Order of Preference by Similarity to Ideal Solution (TOPSIS) was used to rank all configurations. The results show that the optimal configuration achieves the best overall balance between dynamic smoothness and fatigue life, and aligns closely with the field-used configuration, which ranks third. Spearman rank correlation analysis under an alternative operating condition (50% speed, empty load) confirms that the rankings are stable across conditions. The optimal parameters were verified against EN-derived pressure limits and used to specify downstream valve blocks, closing the loop from load definition to component selection. The SSEF offers a practical and transferable approach for standard-driven design and optimization of hydraulic systems.
