TI  - Research Status, Challenges, and Future Trends of Deep Reinforcement Learning in Microgrid Optimization Scheduling
AU  - X. Dong
T2  - 2025 2nd International Conference on Energy Technology and Electrical Power (ETEP)
AB  - Against the backdrop of global energy transition and large-scale integration of distributed renewable energy, microgrids (MG) are crucial for enhancing renewable energy absorption and ensuring energy supply resilience, yet their optimal dispatch faces severe source-load uncertainties. Traditional methods like linear programming are constrained by reliance on precise models and poor dynamic adaptability. Deep reinforcement learning (DRL) provides an innovative solution with its strengths in high-dimensional state processing, dynamic sequential decision-making, and data-driven learning. By customizing state, action, and reward functions for MG scenarios, algorithms such as DQN, DDPG, and TD3 enable real-time optimization for single MG, while MA-SAC and other multi-agent DRL algorithms break through the bottleneck of multi-MG collaborative dispatch. However, DRL applications still suffer from limitations including low training sample efficiency, hyperparameter sensitivity, poor interpretability, and weak generalization in practical scenarios. Future research will focus on optimizing algorithms via integration of model predictive control, meta-learning, and transfer learning, accelerating technology deployment through digital twins and edge computing, and extending applications to integrated energy systems and electric vehicle fleet interactions. This review systematically elaborates on MG scheduling requirements, DRL adaptability, algorithm classifications, application progress, technical challenges, and future directions, providing a comprehensive reference for the field.
