AU  - H. Jeon
AU  - D. T. Nguyen
AU  - M. Zadeh
T2  - 2024 IEEE Energy Conversion Congress and Exposition (ECCE)
AB  - As digital twin technology scales from individual components to complex systems and even entire cities, defining the boundaries and limits of the technology is essential to establish reliability parameters. Designing modeling objects, fidelity, behavior, and characteristics to achieve the technology's goals while considering the interactions within the entire system is challenging. In this study, a structured simulation framework is proposed that derives the required model performance and fidelity based on the technology's application targets and boundary settings. The framework evaluates suitability for ensuring technology reliability through uncertainty analysis and risk assessment. Virtual testing technology for the functional verification of ship power management systems is applied within this process, with modeling and simulation conducted based on the derived results. By adopting a co-simulation method based on the FMI standard interface, connectivity and scalability necessary for expansion into digital twin technology are improved. Compatibility with models of varying fidelity is guaranteed, allowing integration through a cloud-based co-simulation environment.
