AU  - G. Li
AU  - H. Zhang
T2  - 2025 IEEE 8th International Conference on Industrial Cyber-Physical Systems (ICPS)
AB  - Bridge simulators are commonly used for maritime training but have not been widely explored for research purposes. To effectively use these simulators for research, real-time communication is essential. This paper presents a modular framework designed to simplify the real-time interaction with ship bridge simulators, enabling new research opportunities. The framework's modular design allows for applications such as monitoring multiple vessels, making real-time trajectory predictions, or controlling a vessel to avoid collisions. The framework uses a simple structure with multiple threads to handle different tasks concurrently. A case study is included to demonstrate how the framework can be used to make real-time trajectory prediction for a decision support system (DSS). This work contributes to the integration of ship bridge simulators into research, by providing a modular and simple framework to easily interact with the simulator, offering a low-risk, low-cost platform for developing and testing new algorithms.
