AB  - A system-level study of an active phased array antenna is proposed based on a co-simulation methodology combining a digital twin of a radiating panel and measured dataset of a Beamforming Integrated Circuit (BFIC). The proposed methodology is used for the optimization of complex antenna systems, especially to anticipate variations of consumed power and efficiency, depending on the sensitivity of active channels to load-pull conditions and active impedance variations of the radiating panel for different beam-steering angles. The study is illustrated through a Ka-band Active Electronically Steerable Antenna (AESA) composed of a commercial-off-the-shelf (COTS) BFIC and an $8 \times 8$ linearly-polarized Interleaved Parasitic Array Antenna (IPAA). Results from the radiating panel (S-parameters and Active Element Patterns (AEP)) will be combined with the measured Sparameters of the BFIC to analyze the interactions inside the active antenna.
