AB  - Growing demands for efficient ocean data collection in climate research and emergency response highlight the importance of Unmanned Surface Vehicles (USVs) for maritime data acquisition. However, thes USVs face significant challenges, including path planning, obstacle avoidance, and limited computing capacity. To address these limitations and reduce processing time, this paper proposes a USV-assisted edge computing framework within satellite-edge networks. The framework incorporates a data acquisition system utilizing USVs and satellites. Satellites determine optimal USV trajectories based on real-time disaster scene observations, such as signal points and obstacles, to minimize the processing delay. Given the complexity of this problem, we formulate it as a Markov Decision Process (MDP) and employ a Deep Q-Network (DQN) approach to derive optimal solutions.
