AU  - H. Subhadra
AU  - S. R. Vakiti
T2  - 2024 2nd International Conference on Recent Trends in Microelectronics, Automation, Computing and Communications Systems (ICMACC)
AB  - Programmable Logic Controllers (PLCs) have significantly advanced industrial automation by replacing traditional computing systems. A comprehensive approach is proposed for securing critical power systems through a Power Theft Detection and Cyber-Physical Attack Protection System that employs PLCs and Graphical Operator Terminals (GOTs). As power grids increasingly integrate with SCADA systems, the vulnerabilities of unauthorized access, power theft, and cyber-physical attacks become more pronounced. Our system addresses these challenges by continuously monitoring power grid data in real-time using PLCs, incorporating robust encryption, and promptly responding to potential threats. The integration of PLCs and GOTs provides operators with a user-friendly interface, thereby enhancing the protection of modern power distribution networks against cyber threats and power theft. Traditional methods of power theft detection, such as manual inspections orbasic metering techniques, are vulnerable to manipulation and evasion. In contrast, our solution leverages PLCs for real-time monitoring of power consumption patterns and deviations, enabling early detection of suspicious activities indicative of power theft. The inclusion of a Graphical Operator Terminal facilitates intuitive visualization and control of the detection system, while the integration of cyber-physical attack protection mechanisms ensures the system's resilience against malicious intrusions and manipulations.
