TI  - Efficient Low-voltage Topology Calculation Method for Distribution Network Digital Twin Based on High-frequency Measurement Data
AU  - J. Qiao
AU  - A. Zhou
AU  - L. Peng
AU  - S. Pan
T2  - 2026 IEEE PES International Meeting (PES IM)
AB  - The advancement in measurement technologies for terminal devices has significantly enhanced the update frequency and accuracy of power grid equipment monitoring data, resulting in severe computational challenges in low-voltage topology of distribution networks. This paper constructs a digital twin for low-voltage distribution network topology based on high-frequency measurement data, employing graph-relational model to characterize dynamic topology for efficient computational processing. Equipment are mapped as nodes with their terminal numbers used to identify inter-equipment connectivity, while all other devices are characterized as edge components based on connection relationships. The switch-energized-state sequence parsing algorithm is employed to assign node connection weights, followed by spectral clustering to partition the low-voltage topology mapping matrix into multiple subgraphs. Conducting iterative optimization calculation based on energized parameters of diverse switch types to derive dynamic allocation ratios of nodal weights, which achieves optimal topology computation performance. The proposed model is validated through six characteristic low-voltage topology analysis scenarios, including topology switching and line loss calculation.
