AU  - M. Hilmi
AU  - I. A. Kuncara
AU  - A. Widyotriatmo
AU  - A. Hasan
T2  - IEEE Transactions on Industrial Cyber-Physical Systems
AB  - This paper presents a solution for detecting and estimating the magnitude of sensor attacks in cyber-physical mobile systems (CPMS). The proposed approach, encompassing both detection and estimation of attacks, addresses vulnerabilities by incorporating filtered sensor measurements into the state-space model of CPMS. A cascade of nonlinear estimators, including a nonlinear adaptive observer and a linearized Kalman filter, is then employed for attack estimation. Validation involves implementation in simulations with an autonomous vehicle using path-following control and real-world experimentation with autonomous docking of a container truck. Results demonstrate the effectiveness of the proposed methods, emphasizing robustness and high accuracy through low root mean squared errors and rapid convergence of induced sensor attack estimations. These findings suggest wide-ranging applicability across industries, contributing to the safety and reliability of cyber-physical systems.
