AU  - S. Apte
AU  - S. Sandbhor
AU  - Muskan
AU  - N. Jagnani
AU  - U. Sahu
AU  - P. Thakur
T2  - 2025 IEEE 9th International Conference on Information and Communication Technology (CICT)
AB  - India has a 7,517 km coastline with the need for a 130% increase in port capacity over the next five years. The exponential growth in maritime activities and development of modern commercial ports have significant negative socio-environmental impact. Continual development in line with ISO 14001 and ISO 50001 is one way to improve port operations' environmental sustainability and energy efficiency. The practicality of an integrated Environmental Management System (EMS) and Energy Management System (EnMS) is not explored for Indian Ports. A method is proposed for developing an Integrated Management System (IMS) to mitigate adverse environmental impacts, increase energy efficiency, and improve the environmental performance index for ports. The integrated framework is aligned with ISO 14001 and ISO 50001 and is developed considering multiple environmental indicators for ports. Detailed impact assessment studies are performed considering prominent indicators using the matrix and network methods. Strategies for optimal, sustainable and efficient seaport management, are suggested. The framework is analysed for its effectiveness in reducing the environmental impact using secondary data and its AI based prediction till 2030.The proposed IMS can be used to develop a universal port operation model for Indian ports. With improved technical and operational measures, this framework can lead the way forward for Indian port sustainability.
