TY  - CONF
TI  - Cybersecurity in Australian Ports: Incidents, Challenges, and Strategic Responses
AU  - N. S. Gill
AU  - K. Kaur
AU  - K. K. Sandhu
T2  - 2025 5th International Conference on Electrical, Computer and Energy Technologies (ICECET)
AB  - As Australia’s ports become increasingly digitised and integrated into global supply chains, they face rising exposure to sophisticated cyber threats. This study examines the evolving cybersecurity landscape within the Australian maritime sector, using recent incidents, most notably the 2023 cyberattack on DP World as an example to highlight systemic vulnerabilities. The analysis explores how the convergence of outdated operational technology (OT) with modern information technology (IT), combined with limited cybersecurity awareness, inadequate training, and fragmented regulatory oversight, has created a highly exposed threat environment. The paper outlines the operational, economic, and safety-related impacts of cyber incidents on port functions and logistics continuity, particularly in Australia’s interdependent trade infrastructure. It further proposes a comprehensive set of resilience strategies, including zero-trust frameworks, artificial intelligence-driven threat detection, workforce training, OT sensor fusion, and sector-wide collaboration. Finally, the study identifies key areas for future research, such as risk quantification models, resilience benchmarking, and the cybersecurity implications of maritime autonomy. Through this multidimensional approach, the research contributes to a deeper understanding of the critical need for adaptive and proactive cybersecurity strategies to safeguard Australia’s ports as digital gateways to the global economy.
