AU  - G. Venkata Pradeep Kumar
AU  - L. Alluri
AU  - B. Vijaya
T2  - 2025 6th International Conference on Smart Electronics and Communication (ICOSEC)
AB  - In today's computing environments, virtualisation technologies are essential for improving performance, scalability, and reliability, especially for important systems that need to be available all the time. This study assesses and contrasts Hypervisor, Container, and Para-virtualization methodologies by employing performance indicators, including average CPU utilisation, response time, fault recovery time, and system uptime, under simulated workloads and fault scenarios. Experimental outcomes demonstrate that Containers regularly surpassed alternative techniques, attaining the lowest average CPU utilisation (45.6%), the swiftest reaction times (152 ms), and the highest uptime (98.9%) during network failures. Para-virtualization had a balanced performance with modest resource use. Hypervisors, on the other hand, had slightly higher resource overhead and longer recovery, but they did provide strong isolation. The results show the trade-offs between efficiency, fault tolerance, and system resilience. This information can help to choose the best virtualisation solutions for specific needs in high-performance and fault-sensitive contexts.
