TY  - CONF
TI  - A Unified Hybrid Machine Learning Architecture for Battery State Estimation and Fault Diagnosis
AU  - G. P. L
AU  - S. R
T2  - 2025 4th International Conference on Automation, Computing and Renewable Systems (ICACRS)
AB  - The research work proposes an unified machine learning-based framework capable of predicting and monitoring lithium iron phosphate (LiFePO4) batteries, the predominant battery type utilized in electric vehicles and energy storage systems.The battery states namely State of Charge (SOC), State of Health (SOH) and Remaining Useful Life (RUL) are estimated using various Machine Learning (ML) algorithms. The battery faults namely over discharge, short circuit, thermal runaway, capacity fade and degradation faults are classified using various ML algorithms. The ML models like Linear Regression, Ridge Regression, Lasso Regression, Random Forest, Extra Trees, and XGBoost are used for estimation of battery states. For classification of battery faults, Random Forest, Support Vector Machine (SVM), Artificial Neural Network (ANN), XGBoost, Decision Tree, and K-Nearest Neighbor (KNN) algorithms are used. The dataset for the algorithms are obtained from the simulation of Equivalent Circuit Modelling (ECM) of battery. For the state estimation and fault diagnosis ML models are trained and tested. The Linear Regression model performed better for SOC and SOH estimation among other regression models whereas Extra Trees regressor model performed better for estimation of RUL. XGBoost performed better among other classification models for battery fault classification. This framework intends to enhance predictions of failure and support innovations in electric vehicle battery management systems. Future research will test the framework with experimental battery datasets and use it in embedded systems for on-board diagnostics.
