TY  - CONF
TI  - Testing an Automated 20ft Container Truck Using Cameras Plus IMU in a Virtual Off-Road Environment - The Project SIMPAS
AU  - J. I. M. Hauser
AU  - R. Lesjak
AU  - M. Klopschitz
AU  - H. Didari
AU  - G. Steinbauer-Wagner
T2  - 2025 IEEE International Automated Vehicle Validation Conference (IAVVC)
AB  - Highly automated driving is not only a trend for personal vehicles. For the logistic sector, e.g. platooning, automation means a significant reduction of costs. This applies to the civil as well as to the military use case. For automated driving state-of-the-art sensor technologies are LiDAR, radar, and GNSS. While GNSS localization is a very important pillar of automated driving and essential for navigation, it can be disturbed or even lost due to interference effects. Interference is currently very common due to the many military conflicts and also affects the civilian world. Especially in and around conflict regions, GNSS availability cannot be expected. Active sensor systems like LiDAR or radar directly observe the distance to an object by radiating electromagnetic signals. In military scenarios, these signals can easily be detected and hence could give away one's position. For this reason, we designed within the project SIMPAS a navigation system that operates on passive sensors alone, including cameras and IMU sensors, and completely dispenses with GNSS localization. During the project SIMPAS, this navigation system was tested using the co-simulation framework Model.Connect ${ }^{\text{TM}}$ from AVL. The innovative idea is to transfer the established vehicle development process of consumer cars including simulations to the military logistics sector. Rheinmetall MAN Military Vehicles Austria (RMMV) provided a virtual military logistics vehicle, namely a digital twin of the HX2 logistics vehicle for the simulation. The navigation system consists of an AI-based perception module, a localization module consisting of an IMU processing module and an image localization module, and a path planner and trajectory follower (controller) module to repeat a previously driven path. In the virtual environment, we tested the behavior of the navigation system reacting to obstacles and roadblocks, different terrain, and surface conditions. Furthermore, the quality of the system reactions was investigated for different parameters in the sub-modules such as different time delays of the vision-based perception which is a computationally intensive task. This article presents the system design for such an implementation and the individual sub-components as well as test drives and the definition of test cases and possible off-road test scenarios for such a navigation system. We will present our valuable experience and lessons learned from setting up a virtual environment and performing simulation runs. The presented results are important for testing a navigation system for an automated vehicle/truck system before such a system is implemented in a real vehicle, which will be done in the project UMPAS. SIMPAS and UMPAS are funded by the Austrian defense research program FORTE of the Federal Ministry of Finance (BMF).
C3  - 2025 IEEE International Automated Vehicle Validation Conference (IAVVC)
