TI  - An Exact Potential Game-Based End-Edge-Cloud Collaborative Task Offloading Approach
AU  - Y. Shen
AU  - B. Liu
AU  - F. Dai
AU  - W. Dou
T2  - 2022 IEEE Smartworld, Ubiquitous Intelligence & Computing, Scalable Computing & Communications, Digital Twin, Privacy Computing, Metaverse, Autonomous & Trusted Vehicles (SmartWorld/UIC/ScalCom/DigitalTwin/PriComp/Meta)
AB  - With the development of Industrial Internet of Things(IIoT), massive industrial devices produce a large number of delay-sensitive and computing-intensive tasks. Offloading tasks under the end-edge-cloud collaboration mode can improve the efficiency of completing tasks. However, on the one hand, tasks need to be finished before corresponding deadlines and pay for consuming resources, so delay and cost constitute the main factors affecting task offloading decisions. On the other hand, limited real-time resources in the system may not meet the needs of all devices, so we should ensure that as many devices can complete tasks on time as possible while optimizing task delay and cost of each device. To tackle the challenges, we propose an end-edge-cloud collaborative task offloading approach based on exact potential game. Aiming at optimizing delay-cost of each device and task completion rate of the whole system, the end-edge-cloud collaborative task offloading problem is modeled as an exact potential game and solved. Extensive experiments show that the approach can improve the task completion rate of the system while optimizing the delay-cost of each device.
