TI  - High-Speed Video Transmission System Using Multipath Backhaul and Wireless LAN
AU  - N. Yafune
AU  - K. Yano
AU  - K. Mori
AU  - T. Sakano
T2  - 2025 Sixteenth International Conference on Ubiquitous and Future Networks (ICUFN)
AB  - As the information society advances, the demand for high-speed wireless transmission is increasing. Ultra-realistic communication and remote control of IoT devices require efficient transmission of high-resolution video and large-scale sensing data. To achieve future wireless speeds of 1 Tbps or higher, research is focusing on using wider frequency bands and developing multi-stream wireless communication systems. In this context, we are developing an ultra-wideband wireless LAN system using the terahertz band. Our approach combines multipath wireless transmission with a wired backhaul system. This enables multiple access points (APs) to transmit data simultaneously to a single terminal. In this study, we developed a multi-stream wireless transmission system using wireless APs. We also investigated multipath route control by the APs. Additionally, we implemented a load-balancing mechanism. This mechanism dynamically adjusts the packet allocation ratio based on the communication speed of each AP, improving transmission efficiency. We used video data as traffic and incorporated a visualization feature that displays the transmission speed of each route on the terminal. Finally, this paper discusses potential use cases for ultra-high-speed wireless LAN systems based on these technologies.
