TY  - CONF
TI  - Post Quantum Secure Access Framework for Course Material Distribution in Campus Networks
AU  - G. Swaminathan
AU  - A. B. A
T2  - 2026 International Conference on Computing, Communication, Control and Cyber-Physical Systems (I5CPS)
AB  - The transition of educational learning approaches has been successful as a result of technological developments in the distribution of course materials and resources. In the event of a Man-In-The-Middle attack (MITM), the user authentication and key exchange systems are susceptible to being compromised. Cryptographic systems that are considered classical provide keys that are easily discovered by quantum attacks. The proposed work is a framework for the safe delivery of educational resources via Wi-Fi networks, which makes use of Post-Quantum Cryptography (PQC) methods for creating the secure connection and material access via secure terminals. The secure terminal has limited privileges on the hardened BOSS operating system, and it is mapped with the user using a device-binding mechanism to establish a secure trust anchor. A Quantum Virtual Private Network Key (QVPN) is then constructed utilizing lattice-based PQC algorithms to provide robust key creation and verification against conventional and quantum assaults. QVPN protects the data pipeline against eavesdropping and injection threats by encrypting the secure terminal connection to the CMS server. The web-based course repository is only accessible after QVPN setup, ensuring safe academic content distribution. The proposed framework includes a secure terminal, a secure Wi-Fi infrastructure utilizing QVPN, and a content management system designed to establish a robust security plan that will remain in the long run. The proposed methodologies mitigate vulnerabilities and equip institutions for the transition to post-quantum safe digital education.
C3  - 2026 International Conference on Computing, Communication, Control and Cyber-Physical Systems (I5CPS)
