TI  - Terminal-Based Adaptive Cooperative Control and Protection Strategy in Cyber-Physical System Under Hybrid Cyberattacks
AU  - J. Yang
AU  - Y. Zhao
AU  - Z. Wang
AU  - S. Wang
T2  - IEEE Internet of Things Journal
AB  - In view of the complex network interaction and potential malicious attack risk faced by microgrid (MG) as a power cyber-physical system (PCPS), this article proposes a multiintelligent terminal (MIT) adaptive coordination optimization architecture (MITACOA), which is suitable for variable topological conditions, and designs a segmented adaptive resilient control algorithm based on a dynamic event-triggered mechanism (SAR-DETM). The algorithm has the advantages of consistency, event-triggered, and supporting topology transformation, to effectively deal with hybrid cyberattacks, such as false data injection (FDI) and denial of service (DoS). By introducing the DETM related to the attack characteristics, the strategy can be flexibly adjusted during the DoS attack resting period and network topology recovery phase, thus reducing the waste of communication resources. We use Lyapunov stability theory to prove the stability of the proposed control system and its ability to avoid the Zeno phenomenon. In addition, the MATLAB/Simulink simulation platform and the hardware-in-the-loop (HIL) experimental platform, composed of the self-developed MITs prototype, dSPACE real-time simulation system, and an upper server, are used to verify the effectiveness of the control strategy, ensuring the stability and robustness of the MG under complex cyberattacks.
