TI  - Topology-Cognizant Machine Learning for Multiparameter Estimation and Digital Twin of LLC Resonant Converters
AU  - Y. Xiang
AU  - W. Yuan
AU  - X. Du
AU  - Z. Xie
AU  - Y. Chen
AU  - H. Lin
AU  - C. Liu
AU  - Y. Zhang
T2  - IEEE Journal of Emerging and Selected Topics in Power Electronics
AB  - System parameters, particularly those within the resonant tank, fundamentally govern the converter’s dynamic behavior and operational performance of LLC resonant converters. Accurate estimation of these system parameters is essential for enabling real-time condition monitoring, high-efficiency operation, and advanced model-based control of LLC resonant converters. However, due to strong parameter coupling, high system nonlinearity, and unobservable topology transitions, performing accurate multiparameter estimation for LLC converters remains considerably challenging and has rarely been effectively solved in existing works. To address this issue, this study proposes a topology-cognizant machine learning (TCML), which explicitly embeds the converter’s discrete-time topology-dependent dynamics into a neural network architecture. In contrast to conventional physics-informed neural network (PINN), TCML introduces a semi-supervised data-reconstruction mechanism to infer system states at unobservable topological transitions, enabling consistent supervision across discontinuous dynamic regimes. This physics-guided structure compels the network to jointly satisfy observed data consistency and converter-specific physical laws, thereby achieving high-accuracy multiparameter identification under a data sampling configuration compatible with commonly used microcontroller units (MCUs). Furthermore, the proposed method offers additional advantages, including reduced reliance on accurate parameter preestimation, nanosecond-scale digital twin (DT) capability, and online implementation. The effectiveness is verified through both simulations and experiments.
