AB  - This work proposes a cyber-resilient control framework for control-affine systems to deal with unknown sensor/actuator deception and denial-of-service (DoS) attacks. The proposed work's novelty lies in the synergistic integration of double hidden-layer recurrent neural network (DHRNN) and adaptive integral super-twisting terminal sliding mode control strategies along with event-triggered updates to cope with malicious attacks without prior information. The augmentation of the integral terminal manifold and DHRNN satisfactorily addresses the inherent singularity problem and disturbance rejection ability of the control loop. Moreover, a dynamic event-triggered strategy is incorporated into the controller-to-actuator channel to reduce the data traffic in resource constrained environments. Simulation results are exhibited to validate the mastery of the applied controller with cyber-events.
