TY  - CONF
TI  - Privacy-Preserving Fault Detection in Additive Manufacturing Using Federated YOLOv11
AU  - G. A. Sampedro
AU  - M. A. P. Putra
T2  - 2025 International Conference on Mobile, Military, Maritime IT Convergence (ICMIC)
AB  - Additive manufacturing is revolutionizing the manufacturing industry by allowing for the creation of complex geometries and reducing waste. This technology has the potential to greatly impact various sectors, from aerospace to healthcare, by offering faster production times and cost-effective solutions. However, there are still challenges to overcome, such as ensuring the quality and consistency of printed parts and addressing issues related to material properties and structural integrity. Research and development efforts are ongoing to improve these aspects and unlock the full potential of additive manufacturing in different industries. In this research, an enhanced deep learning approach for fault detection in Fused Deposition Modeling (FDM) 3D printers is developed by combining an improved YOLOv11 architecture with federated learning for scalable, privacy-preserving edge deployment. To further improve accuracy, grid search hyperparameter optimization is applied. The results show that the proposed decentralized YOLOv11 model achieves satisfactory performance, with an accuracy of 97% in detecting faults in FDM 3D printers. Additionally, experiments on various YOLOv11 model variants under federated learning settings indicate that larger models provide better performance.
