TY  - CONF
TI  - Distributed Resilient Control for Inverter Based Resources in Shore-Ship Cyber-Physical Microgrids
AU  - Z. Ali
AU  - Y. Terriche
AU  - C. -L. Su
AU  - G. Parise
AU  - S. S. S. Ahmad
AU  - M. Elsisi
T2  - 2025 IEEE/IAS 61st Industrial and Commercial Power Systems Technical Conference (I&CPS)
AB  - The maritime industry is advancing toward sustainability by adopting All-Electric Ships (AES), which depend on DC Shipboard Microgrids (SMGs) to ensure stable, reliable, and efficient power operations. These DC SMGs employ advanced, intelligent, distributed technologies for effective power control and distribution. However, the growing reliance on electrification and internet-based technologies has introduced critical security vulnerabilities, particularly in the control signals and communication channels of Distributed Generator Units (DGUs), including converters and inverters. These vulnerabilities jeopardize the operational integrity of DC SMGs, making them susceptible to various cyber threats, such as false data injection attacks (FDIAs), man-in-the-middle (MITM) attacks, and other disruptions targeting inverter-based resources in shore-power systems. Notably, MITM attacks on inverter control signals in shore-ship DC microgrids underscore the severity of these vulnerabilities, leading to instability and potential blackouts. By intercepting and manipulating inverter sensor measurements, these attacks cause voltage spikes and current instabilities, disrupting the regular operation of shore-power DC SMGs. To address these challenges, this paper proposes a distributed resilient control method to counter bounded and unbounded cyberattacks. The proposed approach enhances system resilience and maintains operational stability by leveraging neighbor system data and employing an average consensus-based regulation mechanism. Extensive MATLAB/Simulink simulations validate the efficacy of the proposed method, demonstrating its superiority over conventional techniques in mitigating cyber threats and restoring DC SMGs stability and integrity.
