TI  - High-Density Shared-Aperture Millimeter-Wave Array Implemented by Circularly-Polarized Filtering Antenna with Hybrid Parasitic Patch
AU  - Y. -L. Lang
AU  - M. Li
AU  - R. Xiao
AU  - X. Chen
AU  - M. -C. Tang
T2  - IEEE Transactions on Antennas and Propagation
AB  - A low-profile, compact circularly polarized (CP) filtering antenna is proposed for millimeter-wave shared-aperture phased arrays. Evolved from a conventional coaxially fed patch antenna, a U-shaped slot is first etched on the patch to excite a pair of orthogonal degenerate modes for CP radiation. And then, one hybrid parasitic patch is located above the patch, which has two functions: One is to introduce additional orthogonal degenerate modes to simultaneously broaden the axial-ratio (AR) bandwidth as well as the beamwidths over the entire bandwidth; the other is to provide the hybrid coupling to achieve out-of-band rejection performance characteristics near 30 GHz without degrading the in-band performance of the K band. The antenna element has a low profile of 0.048 λL and a small footprint of 0.32 × 0.32 λL 2. Its filtering structure is also reusable and can be scaled for dense array layouts. A 4×4 dual-band shared-aperture array is constructed based on the proposed element, covering 19–21.8 GHz and 28.6–32.4 GHz. With the compact spacings of 0.47λL and 0.49λH, the array achieves the inter-band isolation levels exceeding 20 dB (Ka port to K port) and 35 dB (K port to Ka port). Moreover, it supports ±60° wide-angle beam scanning capacity, with aperture efficiency exceeding 80% in the main operating bands, offering an effective solution for high-efficiency CP satellite arrays.
