T2  - 2024 9th International Conference on Communication and Electronics Systems (ICCES)
AB  - Threats using website visual designs and content structures, along with standard coding vulnerabilities, represent an increasing danger to web security. To enhance web security, this paper introduces a new method called cross-feature analysis that integrates the investigation of visual design, live logs, code structures and other vulnerabilities. Based on this threefold correlation, this method identifies discrepancies that might have otherwise gone undetected by traditional approaches reliant on discrete elements. This research rightly provides a thorough methodology for evaluating XSS detection, SQL injection error and time-based testing, CSRF vulnerability checking, clickjacking protection, information disclosure detection, and risk assessment are all included in this. It includes several test vectors for each vulnerability, port scanning with service discovery, analysis of SSL/TLS and security headers, assessment of DNS setup, and integration of WHOIS data. Live monitoring is supported by real-time logging, and actionable insights to strengthen security posture across infrastructure and online applications are provided via a risk-based grading system with recommendations.
