AU  - R. N. Mankumuthi
AU  - S. B. Choppavarapu
AU  - N. K. R. Chegireddy
T2  - 2025 Third International Conference on Cyber Physical Systems, Power Electronics and Electric Vehicles (ICPEEV)
AB  - This study optimizes power distribution in a Triple Active Bridge (TAB) DC-DC converter through phase-shift control to achieve efficient equal and unequal power sharing. Designed for a wide input voltage range the TAB converter maintains a constant output and operates at high switching frequencies with its three ports connected to a high frequency isolation transformer. A feedforward control technique is used to calculate phase shifts based on input voltages to enhance power balance. The research evaluates the impact of input voltage and phase-shift modulation on power equilibrium identifies efficiency losses, and proposes mitigation strategies. A MATLAB/Simulink model simulates steady-state and transient performance under varying the input voltages. Results demonstrate that balanced phase shifts achieve high efficiency with uniform power distribution, whereas unequal shifts cause imbalances, reducing efficiency. An adaptive phase-shift control strategy is introduced to improve performance. These findings advance the design of efficient multi-port converters for Renewable Energy Systems (RES), Aerospace systems and Electric Vehicle (EV) applications.
