TI  - Dual Attention Alignment for Clause-Grounded Instruction-based Legal Question Answering
AU  - S. K
AU  - U. F. R
AU  - G. B
AU  - S. A
AU  - S. M
T2  - 2025 3rd International Conference on Intelligent Cyber Physical Systems and Internet of Things (ICoICI)
AB  - The work presents a QA system that is based on instruction and is imperative in nature, which addresses the legal QA tasks through clause retrieval and answer generation tasks with dual attention in alignment. The model presents two separately tuned attention mechanisms over a user-issued legal command and over semantically retrieved legal clauses, which are combined in order to produce interpretable, clause-grounded responses. In contrast to prior single-attention legal NLP models, our model offers more modularity and transparency in aligning questions with statutory or contractual evidence. The system is taught over a curated dataset of 5,000 instruction-clause-answer triplets obtained from the Indian Constitution, open-source legal contract templates, and annotated legal datasets present in Kaggle. Clause retrieval uses hybrid indexing of both FAISS and BM25, but at the level of LegalBERT embeddings. The system is developed on a commodity machine (Intel i5-1135G7, 8GB RAM) and is served using a chatbot-like terminal interface in Visual Studio Code. Empirical results demonstrate significant gains over a single attention model: BLEU rises from 32.4 to 38.5, ROUGE-L from 40.8 to 47.2, and clause match precision from 65.0% to 78.6%. The system also has support for response logging and confidence scoring, benefiting auditability. The system does not do legal interpretation or rewording but rather answers natural language legal questions for clauses of law. Direction for the future work includes multilingual clause coverage and adjusting based on user feedback to better fit a specific jurisdiction.
