TY  - JOUR
TI  - Observer-Aided Adaptive Consensus Control of Cyber-Physical Multi-Agent Systems With Hybrid Attacked Topology
AU  - A. Anand
AU  - D. Guha
AU  - S. Purwar
T2  - IEEE Transactions on Automation Science and Engineering
AB  - This paper maidenly formulates a distributed secure consensus tracking control framework for a leader-following cyber-physical multi-agent system (CP-MAS) subject to malicious cyber-intrusions. The proposed consensus tracking control framework synergistically combines model reference adaptive control (MRAC) and super-twisting terminal sliding mode control (ST-TSMC), applied to a partially unknown CP-MAS, to enable cyber-resiliency with minimal tracking error and improved chattering performance. Due to stealthy deception attacks on sensor measurements, the states of follower agents are compromised. Thus, to minimize the conservativeness in realizing the proposed cyber-resilient control framework, a radial basis function neural network (RBF-NN)-assisted state observer has been formulated to estimate the uncompromised states of CP-MAS. Using graph theory and the Lyapunov argument, online adaptation laws have been derived that guarantee the boundedness of all signals and finite-time global asymptotic stability of consensus errors. Numerical simulations have been conducted on a group of four single-link robot manipulator agents subjected to hybrid cyberattacks. The presented qualitative and quantitative assessment demonstrates the proficiency and cyber-resiliency of the proposed hybrid control framework over MRAC, ST-SMC, and other reported methodologies in the face of unknown malicious attacks. Note to Practitioners—This study focuses on achieving secure tracking consensus for a cyber-physical multi-agent system (CP-MAS), which has gained potential attention in alignment with the industrial revolution (Industry 5.0 and beyond). With the widespread integration of network-based protocols, developing and integrating a cyber-defensive distributed framework to counteract malicious attacks, without compromising stability and resilience, is an utmost requirement. This paper introduces a novel hybrid control framework that integrates MRAC and ST-TSMC to acquire fixed-time secure tracking consensus for a group of four single-link robot manipulator agents under cyberattacks. A state observer utilizing the REB-NN methodology is formulated to estimate the uncompromised states of the agents by approximating unknown physical uncertainties, thereby refining the consensus law to mitigate the impacts of cyberattacks on the CP-MAS dynamics. The proposed hybrid controller addresses the inherent issues of fixed-time controllers, including the singularity problem, alleviation of chattering, and maintaining a good trade-off between robustness and speed of consensus error convergence. It is worth mentioning that the applied cyber-defensive distributed framework has the potential to tackle malicious cyberattacks, empowering CP-MAS to achieve tracking consensus regardless of physical uncertainties.
