TY  - CONF
TI  - Intrusion Detection for Unmanned Aerial Vehicles (UAVs) via Lightweight Federated Continuous Learning
AU  - R. K. B.
AU  - S. T. S.
AU  - R. N. Shakthi
AU  - M. Madhusudan
AU  - N. S. P.
AU  - M. V. Suvarna
T2  - 2026 5th International Conference on Sentiment Analysis and Deep Learning (ICSADL)
AB  - The Unmanned Aerial Vehicle (UAV) networks are becoming increasingly part of the Internet of Things (IoT), but they are strongly susceptible to the changing and initial cyberattacks because of their decentralized nature. Machine learningoriented Intrusion Detection Systems (IDS) are invaluable to the safety of UAVs, notwithstanding traditional models, which are just trained once. When they are exposed to new and unfamiliar attack patterns, the same models exhibit the phenomenon of catastrophic forgetting in which learning the new threat causes the forgetting of the old ones. To solve this, we introduce a new framework which is lightweight, privacy-preserving and allows Federated Continuous Learning (FCL). To achieve our solution, three main aspects are implemented: (1) Federated Learning (FL) to train models in a decentralized way so that data is not put at risk; (2) Elastic Weight Consolidation (EWC), a lightweight regularization method to reduce catastrophic forgetting by safeguarding critical model parameters; and (3) Differential Privacy (DP) to allow models to offer formal, mathematical privacy guarantees during model aggregation. In contrast to state-of-the-art approaches based on complex simulations with significant simulation environments such as Digital Twins, our framework is tailored to feasible resource-constrained UAV networks. We find our system to be valid on the CIC-IDS2017 dataset, where the system simulates a two-task continuous problem of learning (DDoS then PortScan attacks). As indicated by experimental outcomes, our approach can effectively learn new threats (77.75% accuracy on Task 2) and memorize a considerable amount of knowledge about the previous threat (44.27 % accuracy on Task 1), a strong and superior trade-off between stability and plasticity than a control fine-tuning solution.
