TI  - Combined SoC and SoH Estimation using AI Models for EV Applications
AU  - P. B
AU  - V. Arunachalam
T2  - 2026 International Conference on Computing, Communication, Control and Cyber-Physical Systems (I5CPS)
AB  - Accurate measurement of the state of charge (SoC) and state of health (SoH) is a condition of safe, reliable and efficient work of lithium-ion batteries in a battery management system (BMSs). Due to the richness of the interaction and nonlinearity in the dependence between SoC and SoH, the conventional stand-alone estimation schemes become inaccurate particularly with the change of the temperature. This paper presented a SoC-SoH rapidity estimate model that is temperature-sensitive and based on a data-driven deep-learning approach to learn both simultaneously charge dynamics and degradation behaviour dynamics. Feedforward Neural Networks (FNN), Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN) and Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) networks are used for comparative study. The proposed models are trained and validated using real discharge data from the NASA lithium-ion battery dataset, incorporating practical battery measurements including terminal voltage, load current, and temperature. The SoC estimation performance is systematically studied in different operating areas that is, SoC below 30%, SoC between 30% and 80%, and the complete SoC range from 0% to 100%. The results of simulation, demonstrate that the proposed joint estimation model is more effective than the independent SoC and SoH models. In particular, the joint model using LSTM is highly accurate with Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) of 2.69 percent in the joint SoC-SoH estimation on top of 1.72 percent in SoC-only estimation and 4.51 percent in SoH-only estimation. In addition to this, region-wise SoC assessment gives the RMSE of 0.0281, 0.0279 and 0.0269 in low-SOC, mid-SoC and full-range operation, respectively.
