TY  - CONF
TI  - Federated Learning for De-centralized Self-Healing in Edge-IoT Networks
AU  - H. Kumar
AU  - H. Khera
AU  - K. K. Agrawal
T2  - 2025 Seventeenth International Conference on Contemporary Computing (IC3)
AB  - The emergence of edge-enabled IoT ecosystems has exposed fundamental limitations in conventional self-healing architectures, particularly their vulnerability to single points of failure, latency inflation, and privacy breaches in dynamic distributed environments. This paper introduces Federated Edge-Repair (FER), a novel framework that integrates Byzantine-tolerant federated learning with edge-centric autonomic computing to enable sub-second fault recovery while maintaining strict data locality. FER's architecture combines three key innovations: (1) A hybrid federated learning system employing LSTM-based edge anomaly detectors trained on local temporal patterns, coupled with a Practical Byzantine Fault Tolerance (PBFT)-secured aggregation protocol that reduces false positives by 22.7% versus cloud-based alternatives; (2) An MDP-driven healing orchestrator that achieves 93.4% policy optimality in selecting recovery actions (container migration, QoS adjustment) under dynamic edge conditions; and (3) Zero-knowledge succinct non-interactive arguments of knowledge (zk-SNARKs) for cryptographic verification of healing actions without violating strict Using Groth16 zk-SNARKs with pre-computed CRS[10].Rigorous evaluation on a heterogeneous 72-node edge testbed (Raspberry Pi 4 and NVIDIA Jetson Nano clusters) demonstrates FER's significant advantages: 31.8% faster mean time-to-repair (287ms) compared to cloud-dependent solutions, 18.3% reduced bandwidth consumption through adaptive model specification, and 99.982% service availability during sustained adversarial conditions (15% packet loss, CPU exhaustion attacks). These results are achieved while maintaining full compliance with GDPR and CCPA through FER's inherent privacy-by-design architecture. The framework's combination of algorithmic efficiency (O(n) scaling with node count), cryptographic assurance, and deterministic recovery establishes it as a critical enabler for next-generation edge applications including 5G/6G network slicing, Industry 4.0 digital twins, and tactical edge networks where sub-second failover and data sovereignty are mandatory requirements.
